In this project stock prices data in long format are used to draw inferences from time series data. 6 different stocks from 3 diverse sectors are selected from the data that comprises the closing prices of selected stocks from Borsa Istanbul. The following R-code are written to ensure that these stocks span at least 2 years of data.

stocks <- read.csv("C:/Users/Zeynep Sude Aksoy/OneDrive/Masaüstü/ie 423 project/all_ticks_long.csv")
# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)
library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
# Calculate the total number of unique timestamps for each stock
stock_data <- stocks %>%
  group_by(short_name) %>%
  summarize(total_timestamps = n_distinct(timestamp))

# Define the threshold for 2 years of data 
threshold <- 365 * 26 *2  # 2 years of data since there are 26 data in each day from 06.45 to 14.30

# Filter the stocks with at least 2 years of data
selected_stocks <- stock_data %>%
  filter(total_timestamps >= threshold)

# Randomly choose 6 stocks from the filtered list
selected_stocks <- selected_stocks %>%
  sample_n(6)

As an output of data 6 stocks are selected as below.

“ISCTR”: Banking Sector

“SKBNK”: Banking Sector

“AKBNK”: Banking Sector

“BRISA”: Industry Sector

“BANVT”: Food Sector

“AKSA”: Energy Sector

To identify outliers in the data, 2 different approach are employed. Firstly, for each month in data, boxplots are generated for the chosen indices. To discern any outliers based on Interquartile Range(IQR), this method can be used.

As an alternative approach, 3-sigma rule cane implemented. The data is then visualized using a scatter plot, where outliers are plotted in red and non-outliers in blue.

To explore the reasons behind the outliers in data, each selected stock data is studied one by one

ISCTR

The generated monthly boxplots of the stock data of Turkiye Is Bankası from 2012-09 to 2019-07 is below:

stocks <- read.csv("C:/Users/Zeynep Sude Aksoy/OneDrive/Masaüstü/ie 423 project/all_ticks_long.csv")
# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)
library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Convert the timestamp column to a Date object and extract the month
stocks <- stocks %>%
  mutate(timestamp = as.POSIXct(timestamp, format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),

Moreover, the plot that shows data points falling outside the range of (mean - 3standard deviation) and (mean + 3standard deviation) as outliers is below. The data points that fall too far from the range and their respective year and months are noted.

stocks <- read.csv("C:/Users/Zeynep Sude Aksoy/OneDrive/Masaüstü/ie 423 project/all_ticks_long.csv")
# 3 sigma Rules
# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)
library(dplyr)

# Convert the timestamp column to a Date object and extract the month
stocks <- stocks %>%
  mutate(timestamp = as.POSIXct(timestamp, format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
         month = as.Date(timestamp) %>% format("%Y-%m"))

# Select data for the chosen indices
chosen_indices <- "ISCTR"
selected_data <- stocks %>% filter(short_name %in% chosen_indices)

# Calculate monthly mean and standard deviation for each series
outliers <- selected_data %>%
  group_by(short_name, month) %>%
  summarise(
    monthly_mean = mean(price),
    monthly_std = sd(price)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'short_name'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Flag outliers for each series
outliers <- outliers %>%
  left_join(selected_data, by = c("short_name", "month")) %>%
  mutate(
    lower_limit = monthly_mean - 3 * monthly_std,
    upper_limit = monthly_mean + 3 * monthly_std,
    is_outlier = price < lower_limit | price > upper_limit
  )

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(outliers, aes(x = month, y = price, color = is_outlier)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = paste("Outliers Based on 3-Sigma Rule -", chosen_indices),
       x = "Month",
       y = "Price",
       color = "Outlier") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "blue", "TRUE" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

There should be reasons behind the devaitions occured in studided data. To shed light on the reasons, each outlier data should be examined separately.

May 2013 : In the stock price data of ISTCR, there is an extreme outlier in May 2013. By looking at the outliers in the data of other stocks in any sector, it can be seen that there is a similar outlier occurs in May 2013 in their data as well. The possible reason behind this annomalie can be data errors, either in the recording of the stock prices or in the data processing.

Dec 2014 : In December, annual CPI inflation was realized as 8.17%, the lowest level of the last ten months, more favorable than expected. Hence this may cause an unexpected price increase in stock market which causes 2 outliers point in data.

Also, in November 2014, there is significant decrease in search volume data of ISTCR stock. After November, in December 2014, the search volume increases significantly. The popuarity of stock increases for some reason hence the price fluctuates before it comes to equilibrium.

Dec 2015: In December, the Turkish lira depreciated by 25% against the US dollar and 12% against the euro. As can be seen in the graph below, the trading volume in BIST 30 and BIST 100 stocks, including İşbank, declined towards the end of the year. This decline may be the reason for the negative outlier observed in the data.

May 2016: The reason of the outlier can be a drastic increase in the value of BIST 100 stocks in May 2016 which İş Bankası one of them.

Feb 2018-June 2018: As a result of the presidential and parliamentary elections held on June 24, 2018, a positive movement of TL was observed in the foreign exchange markets.

In order to detect the potentail reasons of identified outliers,Google Trends search volume data of the corresponding stock and stock price data are correlated. To obtain search volume data from Google trends and compare it with stock price data in a plot, below code is used.

# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Load the stocks data
stocks <- read.csv("C:/Users/Zeynep Sude Aksoy/OneDrive/Masaüstü/ie 423 project/all_ticks_long.csv")

# Convert the timestamp column to a Date object and extract the month
stocks <- stocks %>%
  mutate(timestamp = as.POSIXct(timestamp, format = "%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ"),
         month = format(timestamp, "%Y-%m"))

# Select data for the chosen indices
chosen_indices <- "ISCTR"
selected_data <- stocks %>% filter(short_name %in% chosen_indices)

# Calculate monthly mean for ISCTR stock index
outliers <- selected_data %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(
    monthly_mean = mean(price)
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Load the trends data (modify the file path accordingly)
trends <- read.csv("C:/Users/Zeynep Sude Aksoy/Downloads/multiTimeline (5).csv")

# Merge the datasets based on the "month" column
combined_data <- left_join(outliers, trends, by = c("month" = "Ay"))

scatter_plot <- ggplot(combined_data) +
  geom_point(aes(x = month, y = monthly_mean, color = "Stock Data"), size = 3, na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_point(aes(x = month, y = IST.ISCTR, color = "Google Trends Data"), size = 3, na.rm = TRUE) +
  labs(
    x = "Months",
    y = "Monthly Mean of Stock Data / Google Trends Data",
    title = "Scatter Plot of Stock Data and Search Volume Data from Google Trends"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Stock Data" = "red", "Google Trends Data" = "blue")) +
  guides(color = guide_legend(title = "Data Source"))

print(scatter_plot)

As it can be seen from the scatter plot of ISTCR search volume data that is obtained from Google Trends align with the monthly mean price of relating stock. Hence it can be concluded that search volume of the stock are really related to the price fluctuations of the stock.

ggplot(data = trends, aes(x = Ay, y = IST.ISCTR)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Search Volume", title = "Scatter Plot of Search Volume")

May 2013: As it is specified before the possible reason behind this annomalie can be data errors, either in the recording of the stock prices or in the data processing.

Dec 2013: The reason behind the observed outlier in December 2013 can be the fact that according to data obtained from Borsa Istanbul, after merger of VOB and VIOP, a record transaction volume of TL 3,239,319,521 was occured in VIOP. According to ŞekerBank’s solo balance sheet, ŞekerBank, which was the bank that grew and expanded its customer base the best during the period when Borsa Istanbul’s trading volume record was broken, increased its share prices and net fee and commission revenues earned from users reached TL 174 million and its asset size grew by 22.78% compared to the same period of the previous year.

Mar -May 2016: The main funding source of Şekerbank, which attaches importance to deposit development, is deposits. Despite the competitive environment, Şekerbank increased its deposits by 8.53% compared to the previous year and increased its shareholders’ equity to TL 2,532,793 thousand. This caused small jumps thanks to the news even though stock prices were on a downtrend. As a result, the capital adequacy ratio was realized as 13.11% in 2016 and at the same time, total assets decreased from 24.4 to 23.8%, which is one of the main reasons for the continued downward trend.

Aug 2017: In August 2017, Şekerbank announced a partial spin-off of the company. This may be the reason for the deviation in stock prices.

May 2013: As it is specified before the possible reason behind this annomalie can be data errors, either in the recording of the stock prices or in the data processing.

June 2015: June 7 elections are the most likely reason for the negative outlier in the June 2015 data. The 13-year one-party rule, which started with the AK Party coming to power on November 3, 2002, ended after the June 7 parliamentary elections. The political uncertainties following the election results put great pressure on the market. These uncertainties caused the stock markets in Borsa Istanbul to lose 8.15 percent on average compared to the previous close.

November 2018: The stock market investor, the loser of 2018, suffered an average loss of 20.9 percent as the downward trend that started from the all-time high of 121,960 seen by the BIST 100 index in the first month of the year continued throughout the year. Thus, 2018 was recorded as the worst year for stock investors since 2011. This stock market crisis can be the reason of the negative outlier in November 2018

  left_join(selected_data, by = c("short_name", "month")) %>%

    lower_limit = monthly_mean - 3 * monthly_std,

  )

As an alternative approach, employ the 3-sigma rule. Calculate the monthly mean and standard deviation for each series, and flag data points falling outside the range of (mean - 3standard deviation) and (mean + 3standard deviation) as outliers.

ChatGPT

Certainly, you can use the 3-sigma rule to flag data points that fall outside the range of (mean - 3 * standard deviation) and (mean + 3 * standard deviation) as outliers. Here’s a step-by-step approach to do this:

Calculate the monthly mean and standard deviation for each series (stock) based on your data.

Identify data points that fall outside the range of (mean - 3 * standard deviation) and (mean + 3 * standard deviation) for each stock.

Flag these data points as outliers.

Here’s a sample code to perform this analysis in R:

R

Copy code

# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)

library(dplyr)

# Assuming ‘stocks’ contains your data

# Convert the timestamp column to a Date object and extract the month

stocks <- stocks %>%

mutate(timestamp = as.POSIXct(timestamp, format = “%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ”),

month = as.Date(timestamp) %>% format(“%Y-%m”))

# Select data for the chosen indices

chosen_indices <- c(“ISCTR”, “SKBNK”, “AKBNK”, “BRISA”, “BANVT”, “AKSA”)

selected_data <- stocks %>% filter(short_name %in% chosen_indices)

# Calculate monthly mean and standard deviation for each stock

outliers <- selected_data %>%

group_by(short_name, month) %>%

summarise(

mean_price = mean(price),

sd_price = sd(price)

) %>%

ungroup() %>%

mutate(

lower_bound = mean_price - 3 * sd_price,

upper_bound = mean_price + 3 * sd_price

)

# Identify and flag outliers

selected_data <- selected_data %>%

left_join(outliers, by = c(“short_name”, “month”)) %>%

mutate(outlier = price < lower_bound | price > upper_bound)

# View the data with outliers flagged

print(selected_data)

In this code, we first calculate the monthly mean and standard deviation for each series (stock) and then identify and flag the data points that fall outside the specified range as outliers. You can adjust this code based on the structure and format of your data, and further analyze or visualize the outliers as needed.

If you’d like to create separate plots for each stock and display them on different pages to improve visibility, you can generate a series of plots, one for each stock, and use the pdf or png device in R to save each plot to a separate page in a PDF or image file. R

Copy code

# Load necessary libraries (if not already loaded)

library(ggplot2)

# Assuming ‘selected_data’ contains your data with outliers flagged

# Create separate plots for each stock

stock_names <- unique(selected_data$short_name)

for (stock in stock_names) {

stock_data <- selected_data\[selected_data\$short_name == stock, \]

p <- ggplot(stock_data, aes(x = month, y = price, color = outlier)) +

theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# Save each plot to a PDF file (change the file name accordingly)

pdf(paste(stock, “.pdf”, sep = “_”))

print(p)

dev.off() # Close the PDF device

}

In this code, a loop is used to create separate plots for each stock, and each plot is saved to a PDF file with a name based on the stock’s name.
